##Day and night in the shelter

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

The day after he moved into Wuchang's shelter, Fu Dan saw someone picking up litter at a rubbish dump and putting it in a rubbish bin. She wondered why the Janitor wasn't wearing a hazmat suit. A question, it turns out that the person is living in the same ward of the patients, living in bed 159.

By Xie Mengyao

Interview | Xie Mengyao, Wang Yujuan

Editor | Kim Zazu

Cinematography | Yoon hae-won

Shunting

It's not your home. Sweet home, or ever sweet, broken home, or not broken home. A Shelter Hospital is a makeshift hospital, and if you really understand the concept of a shelter hospital, you'll understand all the things it doesn't compare to home. But not everyone knows this at first.

"people are scared. "It was Zhang Wei's first impression of Wuchang's shelter.

She was picked up from her home at 2 a. m. by the community, where an emergency transfer was taking place only three hours before the community received orders. She was told she was going to a shelter hospital, but where exactly, what kind of treatment, how long she would be isolated, "nothing is known, nothing is known. ". That night, she later recalled, there was a particularly heavy rain. The bus waited for three hours on a stormy street. At 5:20 on February 6, she finally checked into the east side of Wuchang's shelter. It was a stadium with a roof a few dozen meters long, and as the first wave of patients to enter, she could see rows of empty beds with white sheets.

"Oh, I didn't know there would be so many people in here, " she said.

In early February, the anti-epidemic strategy in Wuhan shifted to focus on quarantine instead of home quarantine, patients with severe infection, mild infection and suspected infection will be diverted to fixed-point Treatment Hospital, Shelter Hospital, temporary requisitioned community isolation point three different destination. Construction of the first of the three shelter hospitals began on February 3, and the Wuchang Shelter is located in one of the Wembley Arena sites. It took only two days to build, and the first of the shelters were put into use.

Zhang Wei was diagnosed, but the fever was more than a decade old. "I said I was fine, so I wouldn't have to take government resources and this place. "She said. But in fact, the fever can not be used as a basis for no residual virus in the body, high fever can not be used as a basis for the judgment of severe patients.

Fu Dan, who had a fever of 39 degrees, was also taken to a Wuchang shelter on the rainy night of February 6. Technically, she was not officially diagnosed at the time. She's had a nucleic acid test. The results aren't in yet. A tent was set up outside the gym for pre-triage. Doctors looked at her CT scan and said, "it's pretty clear, " so she was taken into the shelter. Sure enough, the nucleic acid test that afternoon came back positive.

She had been running a high fever for more than a week until the evening of the 5th when she was placed in quarantine by the community. It's a three-story hotel with over 60 patients, no doctors, just one or two nurses. "The hotel is very complex to manage, and there are so many floors, it's hard to get a message across, it's hard to call people. " Fu Dan told people, "some people are seriously ill, he had to call his family, the family then managed to get to the hotel gate, called security at the hotel gate, security went to the doctor. All the patients in the hotel were sent to the shelter for screening.

On the first day of the shelter's opening, chaos and order took place simultaneously. The patients were arranged according to the bed number in turn, and the beds gradually became full. Meals are served and medicine is dispensed. There were no volunteers in the cabin, and the medics were busy, wearing the same protective clothing, not knowing who was a doctor and who was a nurse. But the patients'complaints never stopped. "The main thing is that people are confused. Everyone wants the doctor to pay special attention to them. "One patient recalled.

The biggest problem is cold. In order to prevent cross contamination, the air conditioning of the gymnasium was closed. On that day, the lowest temperature in Wuhan was only 5 degrees, plus the rain, the museum was extremely cold and Wet. Although there are electric blankets on every bed, some of the outlets do not have electricity. One nurse remembers that it was even worse in the smaller west side, where "half the electric blankets were dead. ".

As a temporary home, a shelter is not a home. When we started, there was a lot of work to be done. The washstand is a dozen or so column-shaped basins. Installed a water heater, but the use of a lot of people, on the trip, and later people can only use cold water. In order to prevent the spread of the virus in the faecal-oral, all feces and urine need to be handled without public harm, the stadium's toilets closed. The porta-potties are outside the building. There's no time to install the lights. It's dark. Some toilets don't have flush pipes yet. Go out on the way to the toilet did not block, someone wet, come back is a temper tantrum.

The shelter promised to be cleaned twice a day, but no one came in to clean it. In the hall with four water heaters, the floor was filled with water, and the old man walked slowly to avoid slipping. Meals are often served cold. And there's no showers in the shelter. All kinds of complaints.

A young girl burst into tears. It turned out that she was thinking of her mother, who had died of illness. Around the patients have to give her comfort, said the words of encouragement. It was a heartwarming moment, but the overall mood was still depressing and people had to think of themselves. It's true that a lot of these people, the rest of the family, are sick. "said Fu Dan.

Zhang Bing and his family of four were separated in three different places. The 48-year-old was in a shelter, his parents were in the hospital and his wife, whose symptoms had disappeared, was quarantined in a community-appointed hotel. He's got a fever of 104, but he's more concerned about his family. The parents of two or three of his classmates died, symptoms consistent with Neopneumonia, but no diagnosis was made.

At the end of the first day, Fordan found sleep to be a new problem. Second, someone snores. The shelter's on, lights on 24 hours a day. With some valium, she finally fell asleep.

Inside Wuchang's Shelter Hospital, Source: CCTV news

Preparations

Setting the clock back two days, Tang Zhen, a nurse in the radiotherapy department of Hubei Provincial Cancer Hospital, received the order at 3 p.m. on Feb. 4. She signed up after the hospital asked for help on the front line. She is the mother of a two-year-old child, so the leadership repeatedly asked her if she had thought it through and received support from her family; but at the same time, as a part-time nurse in the Department of Hospital infection in Cancer Hospital (including training in prevention of IATROGENIC infection, management of medical waste, disinfection management, etc.) , she is also a front-line badly needed person.

She went to the hospital for a nucleic acid test and a CT scan to make sure she was healthy, and at 8 p.m. that night, she and her colleagues entered the Wuchang shelter. Time is urgent, as the second batch of medical staff sent out by the Tumor Hospital, she was actually two days earlier than the first batch of 40 people set to go to Thor Mountain.

Many things happened at the same time on the 4th. In Changsha, Hunan, the "Shelter Hospital" convoy of 10 vehicles from Xiangya hospital set off early in the morning. If the gymnasium serves as a "viewing room, " These independent vehicles for field inspection and surgery are the key components of the shelter. In Liuzhou, the head respiratory nurse at the city workers'hospital, Liang Yanbing, arrives at work at 7 a.m. , where she and five colleagues board a 4 p.m. Flight to Nanning. The Guangxi team they were part of had 100 nurses, drawn from more than 20 different hospitals.

Later that day, three national rescue teams, including the Xiangya Hospital and other experts, and a total of 400 nursing teams from Guangxi and Hebei arrived in Wuhan One after another. They will work with five local hospitals, including the cancer hospital, to operate the Wuchang shelter as a demonstration site.

While the shelter is still under construction. What impressed me most was that there was nothing but an empty bed. We don't know where the entrance is, where the exit is, where we change clothes. "Leung said.

Each unit has made the division of Labor, Hubei Province People's hospital overall planning, Tumor Hospital assignment task is responsible for hospital sense and material distribution. To be honest, when you first got here, seeing that scene, you really had that kind of mindset that the work wasn't going to go on. Don Poured out a feeling of helplessness. "I don't have a clue about anything. In view of the shortage of doctors, five local hospitals have offered to deploy an additional 18 doctors from each of their existing teams of two doctors and four nurses.

The Wuchang Shelter will have 800 beds and two stadiums for the eastern and western districts. But the oncology team looked at the site and suggested that the beds were too dense, with people standing cheek to cheek in the space between two adjacent beds, which did not meet the hospital's requirements. After discussion, it was decided that the shelter would have an underground level as a third area. The made-up bed was taken away for half an hour.

Another adjustment is to change the floor-to-floor sleeping space from 20 to 50 beds to one-unit partitions. Because you have to put yourself in the patient's shoes. "Men and women, young and old, need to be separated at least a little, " Jun Wang, the hospital's deputy chief of oncology, explained to people. The beds, which had been made earlier by volunteers, were brightly coloured. After the volunteers exit, in order to unify the colors, the medical staff will re-tidied the bed, replaced by white sheets cover.

The transformation will take place overnight. At 4:00 am on the 5th, six dedicated power distribution cabinets were put in place to meet medical needs. The distribution cabinet body is in Ezhou, the accessories are sent by Wuhan, after the Assembly is completed, and then sent back. City building materials market closed, looking for accessories also experienced some twists and turns.

In the invisible, the work is also in full swing. For A two-day Infectious Disease Hospital, everything is new, admission, on duty, transfer of critically ill patients, discharge, hospital sense and other systems, need different working groups to coordinate the development, and written.

At the end of the first working day in the shelter, Tang Chen lay down in the hotel and looked at his watch. It was 4:10 a.m. "Oh, my God, can I go home. "She thought. Can't get much sleep. Got A shift at 8:00.

Operation

By the evening of February 5 th, the Wuchang Shelter had begun to take shape. The Eastern District, for example, is divided into two regions, with the provincial cancer hospital and the provincial maternal and child health hospital each responsible for more than 100 beds. All medical personnel enter and leave from the South Gate of the stadium, while the north gate is used for transporting patients and garbage. There are clean area, buffer area, semi-polluted area, patient's polluted area, and the door is separated from each other.

In addition to the medical staff in the ward work, but also some people need to be on guard outside. Everything is simple. Liang's "office" is actually a changing room with a table for sit-ups. She was here to check that the medics were wearing their protective clothing and to conduct preliminary disinfection with an alcohol sprayer. There is a walkie-talkie in the room, which is used to communicate with the ward and communicate needs. In addition, there are two public mobile phones inside and outside the cabin.

It was as if we were in a real war, with emergency missions at hand. When the national rescue team from Fujian arrived, it was quickly diverted elsewhere. The Guangxi team received full-day training on the 5th. There was no work arrangement at night. At 10 pm, they were suddenly told to send three nurses to the shelter for support. Then the order changed again. The first group (the Guangxi team is divided into five groups) must be in place before 12 o'clock, to fill in for the night shift.

That night after the completion of the team handover work, responsible for external contact Liang yanbing found no car to send her and several other colleagues back. There are cars parked outside, but they can't dispatch, and there's no contact numbers. Finally, after waiting for more than an hour, I took a bus back to my hotel at 4:00 a.m. She had hardly slept all night and had to get up at seven o'clock to lead her team to the next shift. Fortunately, from the next day, the arrangement of the corresponding vehicles to pick up.

Ward staff every shift 4 hours, initially 6 hours, found that the intensity is too strong to reduce. Wearing a hazmat suit, unable to sweat, end of shift, "covered in water. ". Goggles can not be matched according to each person's face shape, in order to avoid exposure, adjust very tight, many people's face was crushed. To enter the ward there must be three levels of protection, inside a layer of isolation clothing, outside a layer of isolation clothing, in the middle is protective clothing, wearing two layers of gloves. It is more careful and takes longer to take off than to wear. The Standard Operating Time is 40 minutes. Bathing also takes up a lot of time, as required, 30 minutes in the gym after going out of the cabin and another 30 minutes back at the hotel. (according to Wu Anhua, a member of the Health Commission's expert panel, it doesn't have to be so mechanical. Just wash it.)

Everyone has to wash for 30 minutes, the hot water supply in the gym is unreliable, the water is cold at the back, and there is no hair dryer -- it was hard to take all the details into account from the start -- it was only a few degrees inside, a few of my colleagues caught a cold. After the coordination meeting, they sent an electrician, the water cooling problem was solved, and the shower room was equipped with a hair dryer. Colleagues with colds and those on their menstrual cycles do not have to schedule shifts.

The operation of a shelter is different from the perspective of the medical staff than from the perspective of the patient. If it's better than living conditions, it's certainly not better than your community. If anything, it's worse than a hospital. A lot of patients come, there must be a psychological gap. "The shelter is a kind of transition point during the great plague, " said Jun Wang, the deputy chief of the Oncology Hospital. "When you get there, you have medicine and medical staff to take care of you. It can have a moving CT, a moving Dr, a moving detector. "

Cleaning is not timely, because it is difficult to find temporary workers, or by the Zhongnan Road to transfer a few cleaners to make ends meet, and then borrowed a few people from the bridge over. The water heater wasn't installed in the first place, so it's hard to get people into the contaminated area. Meals are sometimes cold or not delivered at meal times because they can only be brought in when the medical staff is on shift, and sometimes when communication is poor, one can only wait for the next shift, and those who go in can not go back. "I hate to say it, but working in a shelter is sometimes harder than working in a hospital. I was in charge of his medical care at the hospital, and we weren't responsible for any of that. "Said Jun Wang.

In accordance with the admission criteria of the shelter hospital, only minor patients under 65 years of age with no serious complications are admitted from the community. But the reality is that the community is sending in patients who are not up to standard because of the lack of beds in designated hospitals. For humanity's sake, Jun Wang said, the shelter accepted some of the patients, including a mother in law in her 80s.

To the dismay of some patients, there was no infusions in the shelter and no emergency equipment such as an ECMO. On repeated request, the oxygen supply was not available until the third day. But from the doctor's point of view, transfusion is a creative operation, on the health environment has certain requirements. There were no oxygen machines and ECMO initially, because that's what critical patients need. In theory, patients with mild illness can wait to heal on medication, and once their condition worsens and becomes severe, they will be sent to a designated hospital according to the triage treatment plan.

But the actual connection was not so smooth. Some patients waited in the shelter for a day or two before being transferred out. "The person in the cabin needs to be transferred as soon as possible, provided that there is a hospital to receive him and a bed for him, that you contact an ambulance, and that there are appropriate medical leaders to comment on and assess his condition. So one layer at a time, you're a middleman, both sides talking about you. "said the nurse, Tang Chen. She transferred a few patients, east and West one, to different hospitals, "really a bed hard to get. ".

As a primarily extravehicular nurse, Tang worked longer hours than the in-flight nurses and had to coordinate reports, sleeping only two or three hours a day for the first few days. She also wondered if she could request additional staff at the Oncology Hospital. There are also difficulties at work. Cancer hospitals are not targeted for pneumonia, but they are also understaffed. About a third of the medical staff in the radiotherapy department are in isolation. A colleague's husband, a doctor at a designated hospital, was infected and his family was quarantined. On her first day after, she worked 24 hours straight. A few days after she arrived at the shelter, the hospital sent two more teams to support Shipai Ling and Suizhou. "It felt like the hospital had been emptied. ". She told herself that she would get through the initial stages and that she would be fine once her work was sorted out.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Exterior view of the Shelter Hospital of Wuhan Gymnasium

In fact, as a demonstration point, Wuchang shelter conditions have been considered superior. There are more than 500 medical staff, corresponding to 800 beds. In the 127-bed section of the Oncology Hospital, there are three doctors and a dozen nurses per shift. Every morning and afternoon, a national medical team doctor goes into the cabin to assist. To tell you the truth, we're the only two or three that actually make a shelter. Because it has a national rescue team, so it does have a car, it has a cabin. "A doctor told people.

In the second batch of Wuhan Sports Center Stadium, a Jiangsu Nurse told people that she and her colleagues were responsible for more than 90 patients in a ward for six hour shifts. Her team had been remailing supplies from their own hospitals, but there seemed to be a crisis. They were constantly told to use less. Some of the staff at the Nurses' station no longer wore the outermost protective clothing. "I have less time with patients anyway, " they consoled themselves. The nurse was puzzled. "The rear is tight and we have emptied the hospital. If we don't have enough supplies, will the Wuhan government supply us? "

Hanyang Square solved the patient's bathing problem from its inception -- an electric water heater was installed over the urinal, but the supply did not meet the demand. On February 13, a patient told people that in the three days after entering the cabin, only a box of Jinhua Qinggan granules and a pack of "No. 3 Chinese Medicine" had been distributed in the Hanyang shelter. He was running low on his own antiviral, Abidor, and the doctors kept saying there were no drugs. There's no nurse in the shelter to monitor the temperature, so you have to run to the nurses'station to get the energy. You don't examine me. You don't give me drugs. We actually want medical care, because it's called a hospital, and it's not called a bunker. "He complained.

He ran to the doctor. The doctor told him that these problems are reflected up every day. More pressing is the fact that many of the patients placed in the community do not qualify for shelter and are screened overnight. "eight hours of sleep in three days. "said the doctor.

Cabin life

This sighting was a turning point for Fordan. She was also full of negative emotions, lying in bed did not want to move, "159" infected her behavior, she thought she can do something to do. She found that the hot water area was always wet because the water heater did not have a drain. So she ran outside the museum, looking for a few waste barrels, the pipe into the inside of the drainage, the water will be poured out. Slowly she found that she was not the only one doing this, some people consciously in action.

BED number at first row some confusion, the nurse Liang Yanbing got the task, need to press on the ground to paste a bed number again. She found it inconvenient to pull the tape with gloves on. And a doctor that sticks together with her, wear protective clothing to compare tight, have no crouch body at all. It's not long before a patient comes forward. Posted for a while to rest, and someone relay down, Liang yanbing very moved.

When the nurse dispensed rice and medicine, several people always came forward to help. They took it upon themselves to name the parts for which they were responsible, district one, district two, district left, district right. The oncology team noticed this trend, drew a map, divided the area into Abcde, selected the area from the patients, self-management. At the request of the district chiefs, a loudspeaker was sent in. "armed. Sometimes propaganda. "said Fu Dan, who offered himself as district governor.

That's how you get motivated. Considering that the soup in the garbage always causes the incinerator to shut down, the district leaders called on everyone to pay attention to the classification of dry and wet garbage, and the soup should be poured into the toilet. The sanitary conditions have been improved by mopping the floor and collecting garbage. The 24 hour lights in the shelter kept everyone awake, and Danto's friends who were away bought blindfolds that they didn't have in several stores. Finally, she found a friend who works in a community organization and donated all the blindfolds she had approved for the Children's game.

The "tree of confidence" in the Wuhan Living Room Shelter Hospital. Patients and medical staff can use the post-it notes

The shelter is slowly coming into orbit. The air-conditioning system has been modified to provide heating for the gymnasium, and the room temperature has risen to 15 degrees. Several hundred new quilt, if sleep still feel cold, can cover two beds. The toilets were lighted and sheltered in the open air. On the third day, the oxygen machine arrived. On the fourth day, a batch of books arrived for borrowing.

Critical patients are moving out, and paramedics are checking his sats every day. A psychological consultant was invited to come every day, half an hour in the morning and afternoon, to provide psychological counseling to the patient. Fu Dan felt that laughter was clearly audible in the shelter. There are still people who complain, but they turn around and call home and say, "if you can live here, you can live here. It's safer because there are people in charge. ". "

It's another world out there. On Weibo, you can still see critically ill patients without a bed for help. The worst cases tend to get attention and a lot of retweets. Retweeting doesn't mean it has to be resolved. It's a no-go order for pneumonia infections and suspects, but it takes longer to digest.

There's a microwave in the shelter, there's a TV in the shelter, but there's no one watching it, it's mostly cellphones. The patient that cleans spontaneously takes clothes not much, be afraid of getting dirty don't have to change, request to provide raincoat to drape outside, doctors simply send 4 white coats, some even did not take the number plate.

In the cabin, a variety of daily necessities, from Sanitary Napkins, slippers, soap to nail scissors, after the request is basically met. The purchase requires a process in which the nurses deliver their own shampoo in case the people inside don't use it. Some people want halal, some people have diabetes, so we serve it to them. When it comes in, you tell me which ones are halal, I'll mark them, and when it comes in, we'll tell the nurses which ones, and you don't make a mistake, you send them to him. These are very small details. "Tang Chen said. Someone had an ulcer and wanted porridge. Tang Chen wrote down his needs and reported them.

In the extravehicular world, medical staff may not be able to handle the details. At the Nine Hospital in Wuhan, Florida, a top-tier General Hospital was temporarily turned into a fixed-point treatment hospital, with two nurses responsible for eight critically ill patients and 45 critically ill patients. I was up all night changing oxygen tanks, sweating like a pig. A female nurse in Xiaogan, Hubei Province, works up and down five floors a day, carrying tons of medical waste from the isolation ward, which can't get into the elevator. She eventually passes out on the side of the road due to overwork.

On the night of February 9 th, in a shelter in Wuchang, patients spontaneously performed a square dance. We use mobile phones into the same live channel, the accompaniment has a three-dimensional surround effect. You can't see it clearly. It's not even. It's secondary. It's all about the mood. "said Fu Dan. It's unthinkable in a community quarantine or a hospital, where only a shelter can provide this kind of human interaction. Concerns about cross-infection were expressed to reporters by medical staff, but they did not become a mainstream voice.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In a Wuhan shelter, patients led by medical staff perform a square dance

On the same day, people reporters followed another lead, when a group of nurses at Wuhan Central Hospital were ordered to evacuate after being infected with pneumonia by a chronic patient they were caring for. They are migrant workers, there is no fixed residence, there is no docking community, living on the streets. There is no current process that applies to this group of people. After the press corps spread, the China Youth Daily found them a place to live.

We can finally take a bath in the shelter. Walking down the street, people alert each other. Every day there is fruit and eggs to eat. There are three dishes for every meal, with meat and vegetable. On the day of Lantern Festival, dumplings for breakfast. The patients were told that the standard meal was 120 yuan a day. When a journalist traveling to Wuhan joked on Weibo, "eat better than me, " he was subjected to days of online violence. "shouldn't I eat better than you? "The netizen said to him.

The shelter made a thorough investigation and organized the patients to set up a party branch. Fu Dan is a member of the propaganda committee. Zhang Bing, a police officer by profession and with more than 20 years of party experience, has been designated as the Provisional Party secretary of the Eastern District. Zhang Bing high fever has abated, he is particularly active, a moment can not stop, busy before and after help medical staff share chores, one day down the wechat campaign showed more than 10,000 steps.

In addition to the mainstream media coverage, there was one noteworthy event that occurred during the day: at Wugang No. 2 Hospital, a group of patients were transferred at 2 a.m. , several elderly people were left behind in the parking lot because they could not walk, and the medical staff did not notice. In the cold wind until 8 am was found by passers-by, according to the transfer list to write the name of the hospital, the hospital said not all procedures can not accept. It was not until then that the family of an elderly man received a phone call informing them of the transfer, without prior knowledge of the process.

The megaphone comes in handy again, and everyone sings Ode to the Motherland together. "I'm a little embarrassed before I sing, but really you have to believe in the power of the voice together, including the positive thing, really, really infected everyone. "said Fu Dan.

On February 11, Zhang Wei became one of the first 28 people to be discharged from Wuchang's shelter, the latest of which was on February 9. According to discharge criteria, the patient had no fever for three days, had respiratory remission, showed improvement on CT scans, and was negative for nucleic acid on two tests. "I've lived here long enough to leave. "Some people exclaimed. That was on TV.

As of press time, 13 shelter hospitals in Wuhan had opened their cabins and 13,348 beds were available for treatment. The next step is to build 19 more. A dozen days later, Fu Dan is still waiting to be released from the hospital, should soon, she is ready to pack up clothes, daily necessities and quilt throw away. She noticed that more and more people were dancing in the square and singing in the shelter. There's less bad news.

Wuhan Gymnasium Shelter Hospital
